Explanation:
- This file defines a controller with methods (create, store, destroy) for authentication, but it does not contain any explicit route registrations (i.e., no Route::get, Route::post, etc.) binding a path to a handler. 
- Because API entries require a path bound to a handler and those bindings are not present in this file, there are no API entries to extract from it.
- In Laravel, the actual route definitions are typically located in routes/web.php or routes/auth.php (or similar), which is where paths like /login or /logout would be bound to these controller methods. Since those route definitions are not present in this file, the path strings cannot be determined here.
- If a path string were present as a literal in this file (e.g., as part of a Route::... call) or derived strictly from a framework-supported naming convention within this file, it would be included. That is not the case here.

path.description: The HTTP request path, which must begin with a forward slash (/) and have path parameters wrapped in curly braces ({}). Set this to null if it cannot be determined.
path.title: Path

handler.description: The function, class, class method, or object that handles the HTTP request. Use exactly "anonymous" to denote an anonymous implementation.
handler.title: Handler

handler_in_same_file.description: Whether the handler's implementation is present in the same source code file, rather than being imported.
handler_in_same_file.title: Handler In Same File

path_is_prefix.description: Whether the path string is a prefix rather than a full path.
path_is_prefix.title: Path Is Prefix

path_from_string_literal.title: Path From String Literal

path_from_naming_convention.description: Whether the path string is derived from a naming convention supported by the framework.
